'''Brenden Russell Aaronson''' (born October 22, 2000) is an American professional [[association football|soccer]] player who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] or [[winger (association football)|winger]] for {{English football updater|LeedsUni}} club [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]].

==Early life==
Raised in [[Medford, New Jersey]], Aaronson attended [[Shawnee High School (New Jersey)|Shawnee High School]] for a single year before being selected to the Philadelphia Union's [[Philadelphia Union#YSC Academy|YSC Academy]], where he played soccer and completed his high school education.<ref>Strauss, Robert. [https://njmonthly.com/articles/jersey-living/sports/philadelphia-union-soccer-brenden-aaronson/ "Meet the Philadelphia Union’s Youngest Hometown Player; At just 18 years old, midfielder Brenden Aaronson's dream has come true."], ''[[New Jersey Monthly]]'', May 2, 2019. Accessed June 24, 2019.</ref> During his time at YSC Academy, Aaronson had played for Union's youth teams before committing to [[Indiana Hoosiers men's soccer|Indiana University]] and signing an amateur contract with [[Philadelphia Union II|Bethlehem Steel FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brotherlygame.com/2017/11/20/16671290/brenden-aaronson-philadelphia-union-indiana-university| title=Brenden Aaronson verbally commits to Indiana University for 2019| author=Matthew Ralph |publisher=Brotherly Game| date=November 20, 2017| access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/philly/sports/soccer/brenden-aaronson-soccer-prospect-philadelphia-union-bethlehem-steel-20180821.html|title=Medford's Brenden Aaronson is the Union's top prospect, and a genuine U.S. soccer playmaker|author=Jonathan Tannenwald |publisher=The Philadelphia Inquire| date=August 21, 2018| access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Bethlehem Steel===
[[File:Brenden Aaronson.jpg|thumb|left|242x242px|Aaronson with [[Philadelphia Union]] on March 2, 2019.]]

Aaronson appeared as an academy player playing for [[Philadelphia Union II|Bethlehem Steel FC]] during their 2017 season after coming through the [[Philadelphia Union]] academy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://phil.ussoccerda.com/sam/teams/index.php?team=1400696&player=28259855|title=Philadelphia Union|website=phil.ussoccerda.com|access-date=July 21, 2017|archive-date=November 13, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113165303/http://phil.ussoccerda.com/sam/teams/index.php?team=1400696&player=28259855|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/brendan-aaronson |title=Brendan Aaronson |access-date=July 21, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725004309/http://www.uslsoccer.com/brendan-aaronson |archive-date=July 25, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>
On September 30, 2017, Aaronson made his first start for Steel FC in an away draw versus [[Tampa Bay Rowdies]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.brotherlygame.com/2017/10/5/16428392/south-jersey-teens-impress-in-first-starts-for-bethlehem-steel| title=South Jersey teens impress in first starts for Bethlehem Steel| author=Matthew Ralph| publisher=Brotherly Game| date=October 5, 2017| access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> Aaronson made 21 appearances for Steel FC and scored his first goal for the professional side against [[Atlanta United 2]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.brotherlygame.com/2018/7/30/17629606/bethlehem-steel-players-score-first-pro-goals-in-4-1-win-over-atlanta-united-2 |title=Three Steel players score first pro goals in 4-1 win over Atlanta United 2 |author=Matthew Ralph |publisher=Brotherly Game |date=July 30, 2018 |access-date=January 1, 2020 }}</ref>

===Philadelphia Union===
On September 17, 2018, it was announced that Aaronson would join the [[Philadelphia Union]] at the beginning of their 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philadelphiaunion.com/post/2018/09/17/union-sign-midfielder-brenden-aaronson-club-s-sixth-current-homegrown-player|title=Union Sign Midfielder Brenden Aaronson As Club's Sixth Current Homegrown Player &#124; Philadelphia Union|work=Philadelphia Union |date=September 17, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917215243/https://www.philadelphiaunion.com/post/2018/09/17/union-sign-midfielder-brenden-aaronson-club-s-sixth-current-homegrown-player|archive-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref> On March 17, 2019, the homegrown player scored his first professional goal in his MLS debut, helping Philadelphia tie against [[Atlanta United]]. Considered to be a back-up playmaker for the Union, injuries and suspensions gave Aaronson the opportunity to start and excel in the first team as both [[playmaker|playmaking number 10]] and left-sided box-to-box midfielder.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.prosoccerusa.com/mls/dream-season-continues-for-philadelphia-unions-brenden-aaronson-at-homegrown-game/ |title=Dream season continues for Philadelphia Union's Brenden Aaronson at Homegrown Game |first=Joe |last=Tansey |website=ProSoccerUSA |date=July 30, 2019 |access-date=January 1, 2020 |archive-date=January 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101161955/https://www.prosoccerusa.com/mls/dream-season-continues-for-philadelphia-unions-brenden-aaronson-at-homegrown-game/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

At the end of his rookie season, Aaronson finished second for the 2019 [[MLS Young Player of the Year Award|MLS Rookie of the Year Award]], with three goals and two assists in over 1,640 minutes played. Aaronson was the youngest player out of the five finalists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brotherlygame.com/2019/10/15/20915621/brenden-aaronson-second-mls-rookie-of-the-year|title=Brenden Aaronson finishes second in Rookie of the Year award voting|first=Matthew|last=Ralph|date=October 15, 2019|website=Brotherly Game}}</ref>

The [[2020 Philadelphia Union season|2020 season]] became a breakout year for Aaronson who finished the season with 31 appearances across all competitions and scoring 4 goals. Aaronson's performance during the season earned him several accolades include being named to the 2020 [[MLS Best XI]] for the regular season and the [[MLS is Back Tournament]].<ref name=2020MLSiBXI>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/mls-is-back-tournament/best-xi-presented-bodyarmor |title=MLS is Back Tournament Best XI presented by BODYARMOR |website=MLSsoccer.com |date=August 13, 2020 |access-date=August 19, 2020 |archive-date=February 17, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210217100922/https://www.mlssoccer.com/mls-is-back-tournament/best-xi-presented-bodyarmor |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=2020MLSXI>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/11/20/2020-mls-best-xi |title=2020 MLS Best XI presented by Home Depot |website=MLSsoccer.com |date=November 20, 2020 |access-date=November 20, 2020}}</ref> The Union finished the season with the best league record earning the team's first trophy, the [[Supporters' Shield|2020 Supporters' Shield]].<ref name=SS2020>{{cite news|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2020/11/07/philadelphia-union-win-2020-mls-supporters-shield-regular-seasons-final-day|title=Philadelphia Union win 2020 MLS Supporters' Shield on regular season's final day|publisher=Major League Soccer|date=November 8, 2020|access-date=November 9, 2020}}</ref>

=== Red Bull Salzburg ===
[[File:FC RB Salzburg gegen WSG Tirol ( mit Meistertellerübergabe 22. Mai 2021) 15.jpg|thumb|left|242x242px|Aaronson with [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] in 2021.]]

After persistent rumors, it was announced on October 16, 2020, that Aaronson would join [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] effective January 2021 after the MLS season ended.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=FC Red Bull Salzburg - Welcome to Salzburg, Brenden Aaronson!|url=https://www.redbullsalzburg.at/en/fc-red-bull-salzburg/news/saison_2020_21/welcome-to-salzburg-brenden-aaronson.html|access-date=October 16, 2020|website=redbulls|language=en}}</ref> While the transfer fee was undisclosed, Philadelphia announced that it would be the highest transfer fee paid for an American [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|homegrown player]] from MLS.<ref>{{Cite web|date=October 16, 2020|title=Philadelphia Union Agree To Record-Breaking Transfer Of Homegrown Midfielder Brenden Aaronson to UEFA Champions League Club FC Red Bull Salzburg|url=https://www.philadelphiaunion.com/post/2020/10/16/philadelphia-union-agree-record-breaking-transfer-homegrown-midfielder-brenden|access-date=October 16, 2020|website=Philadelphia Union}}</ref> Early news reports indicated the fee is US$6 million up front, with US$3 million in possible incentives.<ref>{{Cite web|date=October 16, 2020|title=Aaronson joins FC Salzburg in record-breaking transfer|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/soccer-transfers/story/4209284/aaronson-joins-fc-salzburg-in-record-breaking-transfer-from-philadelphia-union|access-date=October 16, 2020|website=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=October 16, 2020|title=Union sell Brenden Aaronson to Red Bull Salzburg for $6 million|url=https://www.inquirer.com/soccer/philadelphia-union-brenden-aaronson-transfer-fee-red-bull-salzburg-20201016.html|access-date=October 16, 2020|website=Phila Inquirer}}</ref> Aaronson made his debut for Salzburg on January 25, as a substitute during a 2–0 victory over [[SC Rheindorf Altach|Rheindorf Altach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2021/01/24/former-philadelphia-union-teammates-brenden-aaronson-mark-mckenzie-make-european|title=Former Philadelphia Union teammates Brenden Aaronson, Mark McKenzie make European league debuts|website=MLSsoccer.com|date=January 24, 2021|access-date=January 25, 2021}}</ref>

[[File:FC RB Salzburg gegen SK Sturm Graz (24. Oktober 2021) 138.jpg|thumb|right|242x242px|Aaronson during a match with [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] in 2021.]]

Aaronson scored his first goal for Salzburg on February 10, 2021, scoring the game-winning goal during an eventual 3–1 win over [[Austria Wien]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/watch-brenden-aaronson-scores-superb-first-red-bull-salzburg-goal|title=WATCH: Brenden Aaronson scores superb first Red Bull Salzburg goal &#124; MLSSoccer.com|website=mlssoccer}}</ref> On May 1, he won his first piece of silverware with Salzburg as the club defeated [[LASK]] in the [[2020–21 Austrian Cup|Austrian Cup]] final by 3–0.<ref name=ACW /> Aaronson scored the second goal of the match, and his fifth in all competitions since his move from Philadelphia in January.<ref name=ACW />

===Leeds United===
On May 26, 2022, [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] announced the signing of Aaronson on a five-year contract, beginning on July 1.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61598449 | title=Leeds United agree deal to sign Brenden Aaronson from Red Bull Salzburg | work=BBC Sport |date=May 26, 2022 |access-date=May 26, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.leedsunited.com/en/news/brenden-aaronson-to-join-leeds-united | title=Brenden Aaronson to join Leeds United | date=May 26, 2022 |access-date=May 26, 2022 |publisher=Leeds United F.C.}}</ref> [[Sky Sports]] reported the transfer fee to be £24.7 million.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11715/12621990/leeds-transfer-news-red-bull-salzburg-midfielder-brenden-aaronson-signs-on-a-five-year-deal | title=Leeds transfer news: Red Bull Salzburg midfielder Brenden Aaronson signs on a five-year deal |date=May 26, 2022 |access-date=May 26, 2022 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> He made his senior league debut for Leeds as part of the starting eleven in their season opener on August 6, with a 2–1 home win over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/aug/06/leeds-wolves-premier-league-match-report|title= Brenden Aaronson inspires Leeds to comeback victory over Wolves|last=Unwin|first=Will|date=August 6, 2022|access-date=August 7, 2022|website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> On August 21, Aaronson scored his first [[Premier League]] goal after forcing an error from Chelsea goalkeeper [[Édouard Mendy]] in a 3–0 home win over [[Chelsea F.C.–Leeds United F.C. rivalry|rivals]] [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], helping Leeds secure their first victory over the Blues for 20 years.<ref>{{cite web |last=Magowan |first=Alistair |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/62537747 |title=Leeds United 3–0 Chelsea: Hosts dominate at Elland Road to continue unbeaten start |website=BBC Sport |date=August 21, 2022 |access-date=August 21, 2022}}</ref>

==== Loan to Union Berlin ====
On July 9, 2023, following Leeds' [[2022–23 Leeds United F.C. season|relegation]] from the Premier League, Aaronson joined [[Bundesliga]] side [[1. FC Union Berlin|Union Berlin]] on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] for the 2023–24 season.<ref>{{Cite web |date=July 9, 2023 |title=Brenden Aaronson joins Union Berlin on loan from Leeds United |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/brenden-aaronson-joins-union-berlin-on-loan-from-leeds-united-23950 |access-date=July 9, 2023 |website=bundesliga.com - the official Bundesliga website |language=en}}</ref>

====Return to Leeds====
[[File:Brenden Aaronson 13092025 (4).jpg|thumb|left|242x242px|Aaronson signing autographs after the [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]'s match against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]]'s match on 13 September 2025.]]

Aaronson returned to Elland Road for the [[2024–25 Leeds United F.C. season|2024–25 season]], putting in powerful performances in his five games in August, which featured him scoring twice in two league ties, including the added-time equaliser in the 10 August 3–3 season home opener against Portsmouth.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cy7686y1k44t |title=Leeds 3–3 Portsmouth |website=BBC Sport|date=August 10, 2024|access-date=September 14, 2024}}</ref> His two goals plus his assists earned him the fans [[JD Sports]] Player of the Month Award for August 2024.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.leedsunited.com/en/news/brenden-aaronson-voted-jd-sports-player-of-the-month-for-august|title=Brenden Aaronson voted JD Sports Player of the Month for August|website=leedsunited.com|date=August 13, 2024|access-date=August 14, 2024}}</ref>

Aaronson finished the [[2024–25 EFL Championship|2024–25 season]] with a career-high nine goals, adding two assists.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Brenden Aaronson Stats, Goals, Records, Assists, Cups and more |url=https://fbref.com/en/players/5bc43860/Brenden-Aaronson |access-date=May 9, 2025 |website=FBref.com |language=en}}</ref> On April 21, 2025, Aaronson was promoted back to the [[Premier League]] with Leeds following a 6–0 win over [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] at [[Elland Road]]<ref>{{Cite web |title=Leeds United 6-0 Stoke City: Whites earn thumping win as they go on to win promotion |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c62glk7vn2gt |access-date=May 9, 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> and [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]'s 2–1 loss to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] at [[Turf Moor]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Burnley 2-1 Sheffield United: Clarets promoted along with Leeds |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cvg70ljnn2gt |access-date=May 9, 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On May 3, Aaronson won the EFL Championship title with Leeds following a 2–1 win over [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] at [[Home Park]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Plymouth Argyle 1-2 Leeds United: Leeds win Championship title as Pilgrims are relegated |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c14xy52vg71t |access-date=May 9, 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On January 7, 2026, Aaronson scored his first brace with Leeds United in a 4–3 loss to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle]] at [[St James' Park]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Waugh |first=Chris |last2=Cross |first2=Beren |date=2026-01-08 |title=Newcastle 4 Leeds 3 — Keegan celebrated in Premier League classic, Thiaw's torment, Aaronson's double |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6937583/2026/01/07/newcastle-4-leeds-3-keegan-barnes-thiaw-premier-league-analysis/ |access-date=2026-01-08 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

== International career ==
[[File:Brenden Aaronson USMNT v Portugal Mar 31 2026-245.jpg|thumb|upright| Aaronson with the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in 2026]]
After showing a strong rookie season, Aaronson received his first senior call-up to the [[United States men's national soccer team]] in October 2019 for [[CONCACAF Nations League]] matches with [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]] and [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]. He did not earn a cap in either match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ussoccer.com/players/a/brenden-aaronson|title=Brenden Aaronson &#124; USMNT &#124; U.S. Soccer Official Site|website=ussoccer.com}}</ref> Aaronson earned his second call-up to the senior team for the 2020 January camp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/soccer/usmnt-january-camp-2020-roster-qatar-brenden-aaronson-mark-mckenzie-philadelphia-union-20191230.html |title=Union's Brenden Aaronson, Mark McKenzie on first USMNT roster of 2020 |author=Jonathan Tannenwald |website=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=December 30, 2019 |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> Aaronson earned his full debut in a 1–0 win over [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]]. Later that year, Aaronson scored his first senior international goal during a 6–0 victory over [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]] in December 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/soccer/usmnt-el-salvador-brenden-aaronson-chris-mueller-20201209.html |title=Brenden Aaronson scores first USMNT goal in 6-0 rout of El Salvador |website=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=December 9, 2020 |access-date=December 11, 2020}}</ref>

Aaronson was included in the 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]], playing in all three group games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/11/09/sports/soccer/us-world-cup-roster.html|title=U.S. Announces a World Cup Roster Shaped by a Wholesale Turnover|last=Keh|first=Andrew|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=November 9, 2022|access-date=November 29, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/nov/21/gareth-bales-penalty-rescues-point-for-wales-in-world-cup-opener-with-usa|title=Gareth Bale's penalty rescues point for Wales in World Cup opener with USA|last=Fisher|first=Ben|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=November 21, 2022|access-date=November 29, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/nov/25/england-usa-world-cup-group-b-match-report|title=Edgy England on verge of World Cup last 16 after fortunate draw with USA|last=Hytner|first=David|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=November 25, 2022|access-date=November 29, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/nov/29/iran-usa-world-cup-group-b-match-report|title=Christian Pulisic strike guides USA past Iran to set up Netherlands meeting|last=Ames|first=Nick|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=November 29, 2022|access-date=November 29, 2022}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
His younger brother [[Paxten Aaronson]] is also a professional soccer player and plays for [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Colorado Rapids]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 17, 2022 |title=The amazing Aaronsons: Brenden, Paxten and their parents on being U.S. soccer's next big hopes |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/37628505/brenden-paxten-their-parents-being-us-soccer-next-big-hopes |access-date=October 16, 2025 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://prosoccerwire.usatoday.com/story/sports/mls/2025/08/20/paxten-aaronson-to-colorado-rapids-reactions-usmnt-transfer/85738181007/|title='Paxten Aaronson To Colorado Rapids'}}</ref>

Aaronson's performances for the Philadelphia Union and Red Bull Salzburg earned him the nickname of the "Medford Messi", an [[alliteration]] that refers to his birthplace and makes a comparison with Argentine player [[Lionel Messi]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=August 4, 2021|title=Brenden Aaronson, aka "The Medford Messi" Scores Game Winner Against Barcelona|url=https://www.crossingbroad.com/2021/08/brenden-aaronson-aka-the-medford-messi-scores-game-winner-against-barcelona.html|access-date=August 5, 2021|website=Crossing Broad|language=en-US}}</ref> He is a fan of the [[San Francisco 49ers]], as his father is from Sacramento.<ref>{{Citation |title=Brenden Aaronson Opens Up On Highs & Lows of Early Career | date=October 16, 2023 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vD_mqU7MB4Q |access-date=October 16, 2023 |language=en}}</ref>

He became engaged to Milana D'Ambra in August 2024.<ref>{{Cite Instagram |postid=C-Vr-I6oPMg|user=baaronson7|title=Loved you every day since we were 16 and now we are getting married 💛 Can't wait for forever with you!|date=August 6, 2024}}</ref>

